the 16 soviet students have been in new hampshire since late 
june part of an exchange in which 16 americans mostly from 
dartmouth spent about six weeks at moscow state university the 
students major in areas including chemistry molecular biology and 
biophysics 
most have completed four years of their fiveyear college 
studies and will likely be scientists teachers and researchers in 
the soviet union which is trying to deal with the same 
environmental problems plaguing the united states water and air 
pollution acid rain hazardous waste and trash disposal 
the outing to the dump and signal environmental systems 
refusetoenergy plant in claremont was the first time the students 
met reporters which meant interviews atop claycovered mounds of 
trash next to cans of discarded copper tubing or next to a garbage 
truck being weighed before dumping its load at the incinerator 
they drove from the hot dusty dump to an adjacent hotter and 
dustier metal recycling area where a shirtless fred janci of janci 
metal and recycling explained his business 
dimitrij kavtaradze a moscow state professor teaching at 
dartmouth this year picked up a horseshoe this is the best 
souvenir from america good luck and asked janci if he could 
keep it 
janci said yes 
after seeing how trash is buried or prepared for reuse it was 
off to the incinerator to learn about another way to dispose of 
refuse burning again taking pictures and notes 
professor burdin konstantin also from moscow state said the 
main purpose of the visit is to learn how the united states deals 
with environmental problems 
the main thing is to see what kinds of problems are in the 
united states and how do you solve these problems konstantin 
said 
the united states he said is on the frontier of dealing 
with environmental problems the american experience he said 
should help soviets struggling with the same problems especially 
with questions of balancing growth with the environment and even 
with citizen opposition to construction projects such as a sewer 
proposal that prompted protest near moscow 
and the exchange experience may help his students understand 
more about america 
we should understand people we should understand problems we 
cannot separate problems and people he said in some ways its 
people diplomacy 
some of the students talked about their first impressions of the 
united states saying they were impressed with the highways and 
friendly people 
they are very friendly people said olga divovich of moscow 
they often smile at us and its very pleasant for us 
</TEXT>
