<TEXT>
here at a glance are some facts and figures 
about the election in mexico 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the presidency four men and one woman are running for a 
single sixyear term that begins dec 1 the three major 
candidates are carlos salinas de gortari of the ruling 
institutional revolutionary party known as the pri cuauhtemoc 
cardenas of the leftist national democratic front coalition and 
manuel j clouthier of the conservative national action party also 
running are rosario ibarra de piedra of the radical revolutionary 
workers party and gumersindo magana negrete of the tiny mexican 
democratic party 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the senate voters elect 64 senators two from each of mexicos 
31 states and two from the federal district like presidents 
senators serve six years and cannot be reelected mexico has had 
only one opposition senator under pri rule 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
chamber of deputies 500 members of the lower house will be 
elected for threeyear terms expanding the size of the current 
chamber by 100 the ruling party has 289 seats the rest are spread 
among nine opposition parties 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the issues election fraud a stagnating economy hobbled by 
inflation and a massive foreign debt 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the voters about 38 million out of an estimated 80 million 
population are registered more than 10 percent have five years or 
less education more than 61 percent are under 40 the electorate 
is about evenly split between men and women 
</TEXT>
