<DOCNO> AP880707-0065 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
last years mild el nino a puzzling 
phenomenon in which global weather disruptions follow a warming of 
the pacific was predicted by three different climate models 
according to scientists who hope they can now serve distant warning 
of future recurrences 
looking at the results we feel there is a good chance of 
being able to assess these things as much as a year ahead and over 
time we expect to get better said stephen zebiak of the columbia 
universitys lamontdoherty geological laboratory 
time will show how much value these kinds of models and 
predictions can have until there is a consensus on that we dont 
expect to see governments taking action readily based on them 
although i do think that eventually that will happen zebiak said 
thursday in a telephone interview 
its a new kind of game really a lot of people are still 
quite skeptical about it 
the successful predictions of the 198687 el nino are being 
formally reported in fridays edition of science magazine 
el ninos still not fully understood are events that appear to 
affect weather around the world one that occurred in 198283 
described as the strongest in this century was blamed for an 
estimated 1500 deaths and damage of 2 billion to 8 billion 
worldwide 
the 198687 el nino had much less impact although some unusual 
weather was reported including heavy rains in coastal peru and 
drought in india and the pacific northwest of the united states 
the events are preceded by unusually warm water temperatures in 
the pacific and changes in barometric pressure over that ocean 
zebiak said the climate studies currently show cooler than 
normal pacific ocean temperatures the opposite of an el nino 
for at least the balance of this year these cold events do not 
seem to have the climate impact of the warmer el ninos he added 
el ninos take their name from the spanish word for child a 
reference to the christ child this was coined by peruvian 
fishermen to refer to the recurring phenomenon which sharply 
reduced their fish supply and was often first noticed at christmas 
time 
scientists combining that name with a reference to changes in 
pacific and indian ocean air pressure usually use the term enso 
for el ninosouthern oscillation 
the three different climate models that predicted the 198687 el 
nino were 
the lamontdoherty model developed by mark cane zebiak and 
sean dolan this model uses a computer to calculate changes in the 
ocean and atmosphere and their relations with one another termed 
a dynamic model meaning it uses mathematical formulas to 
calculate changes it predicted the el nino more than a year ahead 
of time 
a model based primarily on changing ocean conditions coupled 
with unusual wind currents developed by james obrien and d 
legler of florida state university this combined dynamic and 
statistical information and can issue predictions a few months in 
advance zebiak explained 
a statistical model using wind patterns and sealevel air 
pressure readings over the pacific and indian oceans which can 
give predictions with lead times of 3 to 9 months this pair or 
related models was developed by timothy barnett and nicholas e 
graham at scripps institute of oceanography in la jolla calif 
in the case of the 198687 el nino all three models wound up 
making the same prediction just at different times zebiak said 
it is interesting that different models which are based on 
quite different kinds of approaches are showing consistency i 
think it is basically encouraging another piece of evidence that 
there really is a robust kind of signal here which we are 
capturing in different ways 
the fact is that these kind of forecasts are a reality now 
they will continue we and the other people are doing it sort of 
routinely now what remains to be assessed is the kind of feeling 
for exactly how reliable they are going to be in the situations 
that nature throws our way zebiak said 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
