<TEXT>
a new test to quickly estimate blood 
cholesterol levels won approval thursday from the food and drug 
administration 
the new device quicker and easier to use than current tests 
uses a drop of blood on a chemically treated card that changes 
color according to the amount of cholesterol in the blood 
the test to be available for use by physicians is intended 
only as a preliminary screening technique to identify people with 
elevated cholesterol levels who may need treatment 
people with high readings on the screening test should receive 
further evaluation with conventional lab tests the fda said 
the new test does not give a count but indicates whether the 
sample tested falls within three ranges below 200 milligrams per 
deciliter from 200 to 300 milligrams or over 300 milligrams 
federal officials health officials urge further evaluation for 
anyone with a level above 200 milligrams per deciliter 
the new test called clinicard is made by chemelec inc 
of north webster ind and will be available on a limited basis in 
about a month the fda said 
