<TEXT>
a sophisticated test that allows 
detection of minute amounts of the aids virus in people who by 
conventional tests appear uninfected is being offered commercially 
by two california laboratories 
the test uses a technique called polymerase chain reaction or 
pcr in which extremely small amounts of genetic material can be 
picked out and quickly copied to provide enough material for 
analysis 
it has been used in rare cases to identify people carrying small 
amounts of the aids virus but who tested negative on conventional 
tests 
the pcr test does not detect only aids but any tiny amounts of 
genetic material it has previously been available only for 
research 
cetus corp which developed the technique on wednesday 
announced it has licensed the pathology institute in berkeley and 
specialty laboratories inc in santa monica to use the test 
physicians or laboratories will be able to send them blood samples 
for testing which takes five days and costs about 145 
the pcr technique is not intended to replace the standard elisa 
test which detects antibodies to the acquired immune deficiency 
syndrom virus 
in many cases the aids virus does not trigger production of 
antibodies for six months or more after the infection has occurred 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

