<TEXT>
federal health officials reported thursday the 
nations first case of human anthrax since 1984 in a textile 
worker believed infected by contaminated cashmere 
a 42yearold maintenance man at a north carolina mill became 
ill last july with a small red lesion on his arm and developed 
pain fever and chills over the following week the centers for 
disease control reported he was diagnosed with a cutaneous form of 
anthrax a severe and potentially fatal disease most common in 
cattle and sheep 
only nine human cases have occurred in the united states in the 
last decade none since 1984 the cdc said 
the patient who recovered hadnt recently been out of north 
carolina or been exposed to animals or animal materials however 
the cdc noted his mill uses wool imported from australia and new 
zealand cashmere goat hair from china afghanistan and iran and 
camel hair from china and mongolia 
eight of 59 textile samples tested at the mill including five 
samples of west asian cashmere showed contamination with anthrax 
bacteria the cdc said in its weekly report 
the west asian cashmere was probably the contaminant the 
cdc reported western asia is an endemic area for anthrax 
the other three contaminated samples were either debris or 
australian wool which may have been crosscontaminated while stored 
near the cashmere the atlantabased agency said 
this case demonstrates that the potential for occupational 
transmission of anthrax still exists the cdc said 
vaccination programs were recommended for workers at the north 
carolina plant and at a texas plant where the cashmere was washed 
said the cdc which as is its custom did not identify the 
locations involved 
</TEXT>
