<TEXT>
the house grappling with one of its most 
sensitive political issues sidestepped a decision thursday on 
whether to let the pentagon shut down unneeded military bases 
the chamber was considering a pair of plans setting up complex 
mechanisms and procedures for closing some of the 3800 military 
installations around the nation pentagon officials estimate that 
between 2 billion and 5 billion annually could be saved by 
shutting unneeded bases 
but after a preliminary test vote the chamber dropped the bill 
in part because the debate had run longer than scheduled house 
members generally do not work past thursday afternoons permitting 
members from western states to return home for electionyear 
campaigning 
for the past 11 years congress has blocked any base closings 
because closings mean lost jobs and lawmakers have been loath to 
see payrolls cut 
but the federal budget deficit has forced congess to take 
another look at the closings and rep william dickinson rala 
noted that this is also a politically opportune time to act 
many things have come together to make this possible 
dickinson said we have a window of opportunity we have a 
lameduck congress we have a lameduck administration a lameduck 
secretary of defense 
defense secretary frank c carlucci has appointed a ninemember 
commission to review the nations military facilities and decide by 
the end of the year which can be closed that commission has been 
meeting for the past two months 
under the two plans considered thursday the commission would 
send its report to president reagan next dec 31 who would then 
have until shortly before he leaves office next jan 20 to either 
accept or reject the entire list the president could not pick or 
choose from among the bases 
then under a plan proposed by rep dick armey rtexas the 
bases would be closed starting jan 1 1990 unless both the house 
and senate voted against the list 
but under the second plan the closings could not go forward 
unless both chambers voted in favor of the plan 
the second plan was backed by three committees which jointly 
agreed to overhaul the original armey plan 
the house in what house armed services committee chairman les 
aspin dwis called a key test of views on the issue voted 
250138 in support of an amendment providing that the base closures 
would go ahead unless both the house and senate vote to block them 
that provision by rep john kasich rohio is similar to the 
plan proposed by armey the amendment was added to the 
committeebacked bill 
rep jack brooks dtexas chairman of one of the three panels 
the government operations committee said congress should have to 
vote to approve any closings 
the armey plan is designed to circumvent the political 
process brooks told his colleagues 
but rep constance morella rmd said the armey proposal is 
the only way we can get this done 
in addition to requiring an affirmative rather than a negative 
vote the committeebacked plan would also require the pentagon to 
come up with plans to restore the environment at each outdated 
base along with new studies about the economic impact of the 
closings 
rep les aspin dwis chairman of the armed services 
committee noted that pentagon budgets are declining the 
congress ought to take every opportunity we can to make sure the 
money we spend on defense is spent wisely 
in the decades after world war ii when the nation was winding 
down from a largescale military structure the pentagon was 
generally allowed to do what it wanted on the issue with the 
exception of a handful of bases protected by key powerful members 
between 1961 and 1977 the pentagon closed 3600 installations 
but in 1975 the air force proposed shutting down loring air 
force base in northern maine that states legislators blocked the 
procedure by requiring lengthy and costly environmental impact 
studies for the loring closing and all future closings since 1977 
no major facilities have been shut 
armeys proposal was defeated last year 199192 but he decided 
to try again because circumstances were different 
house approval would send the plan to the senate which voted 
for its own baseclosing plan two months ago 
that proposal creating a 15member commission was attached to 
a pentagon budget bill but was later dropped by the housesenate 
conference committee called to resolve differences between the two 
chambers over the defense budget 
</TEXT>
