<TEXT>
the mortal remains of hungarianborn 
composer bela bartok were laid to final rest thursday in the family 
tomb on a budapest hillside 43 years after he died of leukemia in 
new york 
at least 5000 hungarians thronged the small farkasret cemetery 
for the reburial including foreign minister peter varkonyi and 
pianist annie fischer 
bartok one of the leading composers of the 20th century was 
born in 1881 in transylvania he left hungary in 1940 in disgust 
over its close ties with nazi germany and emigrated to the united 
states where he died five years later 
this is a welcome home and a last farewell rolled into one 
solemn ceremony jozsef ujfalussy former director of the franz 
liszt academy of music told the mourners his music created a 
new world that extended mankinds artistic horizons and tends to 
universality 
he set a great human example for mans search for freedom and 
humanity and his remains now return to a nation in quest of a 
newly found selfawareness said ujfalussy author of several 
monographs on bartok 
as part of a unitarian burial ceremony bishop joszef ferencz 
delivered a funeral oration extolling bartoks human qualities and 
moral standing 
a monument of swedish black granite the work of scupltor miklos 
borsos marked the burial place borsos said it symbolizes an 
apotheosis of music the soul as a takingoff bird 
bartok was reburied next to his two wives his mother and an 
aunt and near his greatest friend and collaborator zoltan kodaly 
the remains were exhumed at new yorks ferncliff cemetery june 
21 a brass plaque that marked bartoks grave there was buried with 
him at farkasret 
the ceremony was broadcast live by this communistruled nations 
state radio and television 
peter bartok 64 who lives in homosassa fla and bela bartok 
jr 78 accompanied their fathers remains from new york on the 
liner queen elizabeth ii and then through france west germany and 
austria the elder son lives in budapest and is president of 
hungarys unitarian church 
a religious choir sang the hymn we have placed our faith in 
the lord at the funeral service thursday then ferencz spiritual 
leader of hungarys 10000 unitarians praised bartok for adopting 
the faith in 1916 
this faith is humane tolerance itself very much an embodiment 
of what he stood for as a musician and a man he said 
vice president rezsoe trautmann spoke after the unitarian 
service he criticized some of the dogmatic events of the early 
1950s when bartoks music was oficially frowned upon as 
formalist and effectively disappeared from concert programs 
the return of his remains now is a great solace for the nation 
as a whole trautmann said 
at least 10000 hungarians and hundreds of foreign visitors 
wednesday paid their last respects to bartoks remains at the 
academy of sciences building 
