<TEXT>
the piper alpha platform destroyed in 
the worst offshore oil rig disaster was an assembly of flatroofed 
structures and steel towers that rose 150 above the water 
it was 215 feet long and 100 feet wide among the largest of the 
123 fixed platforms that dot the british sector of the north sea 
oil field a fire burned constantly at its top flaming off excess 
gas 
the 901 million piper alpha owned by occidental petroleum 
began pumping oil and gas in december 1976 from its location 120 
miles off eastern scotland and was among the oldest of the north 
sea rigs 
last year the 34000ton platform produced a daily average of 
23 million cubic feet of gas and 167200 barrels of oil 
it was linked to four other platforms in one of the most 
profitable sectors of the north sea field discovered in the 1960s 
more than 200 men worked the piper alpha earning up to 1000 a 
week in dangerous jobs they lived on the platform for up to two 
weeks at a time on a duty schedule of 12 hours on and 12 off 
the piper alpha was pinned to the sea bed and supported by steel 
stilts with most of its 649foot height submerged it included a 
helicopter landing pad used to ferry the workers out from aberdeen 
and had lifeboats with a total capacity of 300 people 
