<DOCNO> AP880707-0138 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the 1979 crash of an air new zealand dc10 
into a mountain in antarctica was the result of crew error and not 
any fault of navy air traffic controllers a judge ruled thursday 
us district judge harold h greene blamed the airline and the 
crew of flight 901 for a series of mistakes that caused the plane 
to fly off course into mt erebus killing all 257 people on board 
greene dismissed 32 million in negligence claims against the 
us government by relatives and heirs of 16 of the 20 crew members 
who died in the nov 28 1979 crash on ross island in antarctica 
the judge blamed the airline for changing the original flight 
plan for the sightseeing trip without briefing the crew he also 
cited the crews failure to use the airliners internal navigation 
device and a weather radar system to determine its location 
were it not for the tragic outcome the planning phase of 
flight 901 could be described as a comedy of errors some of these 
errors were perpetrated by air new zealand others by members of 
the flight crew greene said 
the change in the flight plan put the plane directly in a course 
over mt erebus instead of down the center of mcmurdo sound the 
plan called for flight 901 to avoid the mountain by flying at an 
altitude of 16000 feet 
to give passengers a better view of ross island the plane 
descended without radar assistance to less than 2000 feet in 
violation of air new zealand policy greene said 
it was flying at an altitude of 1500 feet when it crashed into 
mt erebus 
the crew never discovered the change because it never bothered 
to plot the coordinates of the new flight plan greene said nor 
did crew members bother to use the planes internal navigation 
system to determine its geographical location 
had a single crew member performed this simple task at any 
time during the last hour of flight he would have learned that the 
aircraft was not on longitude 165 degrees heading down the open 
sound but on a longitude of 167 degrees heading toward mt 
erebus 
if the crew were more alert it would have noticed that beaufort 
island was to the planes right instead of the left as it would 
have been if flight 901 had flown on the original course greene 
said 
the air traffic controllers at mcmurdo station had no reason 
to suspect that these errors in the most fundamental principles of 
planning and airmanship had occurred and that they had profoundly 
altered what would otherwise have been a safe and uneventful 
flight greene said 
absent such knowledge they had no basis for suspecting that 
flight 901 was in mortal peril or for taking extraordinary 
measures that even the flight crew never requested them to take 
greene said 
the navys air traffic controllers are assigned to mcmurdo 
station to help direct aircraft used in scientific exploration by 
the national science foundation and other organizations 
</TEXT>
