<TEXT>
apple consumption in the united states has 
risen to a record 20 pounds per person this year good news for 
growers saddled with last years largest crop in history the 
washington apple commission said thursday 
the nation has produced about 130 million 42pound boxes of 
apples this season with washington growing about 67 million of 
those the commission reported 
we never had the supply nationally to really find out if 
people would eat more apples said charles st john spokesman 
for the industry marketing group based in wenatchee 
a lot of skeptics have said the industry cannot increase apple 
production because americans will not eat more apples st john 
said this year weve found that people will eat more apples 
using its own unofficial projection methods the commission has 
determined that apple consumption will be 216 pounds per person 
this year up significantly from last years 184 pounds per 
person st john said 
that is the only time since 1970 date of the earliest research 
that apple consumption has topped 20 pounds per person he said 
normal consumption since 1970 has been 17 to 18 pounds per 
person with a high of 199 pounds in 1975 which was another 
bumper crop year st john said 
consumption has been pushed up this year by the combination of a 
massive crop low prices and extensive marketing activities 
washingtons 67 million boxes in 1987 easily eclipsed the 
previous years record of 55 million boxes 
but the huge crop lowered prices to below the 950 per box cost 
of production for much of the year 
only since the first of the month have prices jumped up and 
currently are up to 19 per box for top grades according to market 
news service 
this year has been an economic disaster from the growers 
perspective said st john although the consumption projections 
provide a silver lining in that dark cloud 
the current apple season ends in august when the remaining 44 
million boxes of washington apples still in storage will be gone 
st john said 
early projection for the 1988 crop indicate it will be smaller 
because of this years low prices and because irrigation water 
supplies in the yakima valley are lower than normal due to last 
years northwest drought 
the projections were created by the commission which used 
production reports from around the nation subtracted known exports 
and divided the remainder by the nations population st john 
said we came as close as we can to a true domestic consumption 
figure he said 
washington which accounts for about 90 percent of apple 
exports has shipped a record 122 million boxes to other nations 
so far this year well above last years 52 million boxes 
the us consumption figure does not take into account imports 
from other nations so consumption may actually be higher st john 
said 
the projections assume all apples shipped to the fresh market 
are sold and do not include apples processed into juice applesauce 
and other products he said 
the amount of apples sold for processing for less money varies 
each year and depends on how many were undesirable for the fresh 
market because of weather damage or undesirable color about a 
quarter of washingtons crop usually goes to processors but up to 
a third of the 1987 crop was unfit for the fresh market in other 
growing areas up to half of the crop may go to processors 
</TEXT>
