<TEXT>
the nations two largest financial markets took 
a joint step thursday toward averting another stock crash 
proposing reforms that include special attention to small investors 
and coordinated trading halts when the dow jones industrial average 
falls 250 points 
the announcement by the boards of the new york stock exchange 
and chicago mercantile exchange addressed many of the key issues 
raised by government studies on the causes of the october crash 
particularly the need for cooperation between the nations 
financial markets 
it also marked the most comprehensive action yet taken by the 
securities industry to reform itself since then and convince 
millions of crashburned investors that the markets are safe and 
fair 
had the joint measures been in place oct 19 the unprecedented 
508point plunge in the dow average would have been averted 
we have developed a program of coordinated procedures which 
serve the current needs of financial markets cme chairman leo 
melamed said these combined initiatives demonstrate our 
commitment to serving the needs of all investors and ensuring a 
level playing field for all market participants 
nyse chairman john phelan said that although markets have 
returned to more normal patterns there is still a perception 
that individuals are at a disadvantage in todays highspeed 
markets the initiatives approved by the boards should overcome 
that concern 
all of the initiatives must be approved by the securities and 
exchange commission which oversees the nations stock markets and 
the commodities futures trading commission which regulates the 
futures markets 
the steps include a system for expediting trading orders of 
individual investors to the nyse floor on heavy trading days 
during the crash many individuals were unable to sell their stock 
quickly because the markets system was clogged with sell orders 
from large institutional investors 
both exchanges also proposed a oneyear experimental system of 
coordinated circuit breaker mechanisms to forestall panicky 
selling when the dow average is falling rapidly 
under this system which must be approved by other markets and 
the securities and exchange commission all trading on the nyse 
would be halted for an hour if the dow average falls 250 points 
and for two hours if the average falls an additional 150 points the 
same day 
at the cme the key standard amp poors 500 stockindex future 
could fall a maximum 30 points before trading would be halted a 
twohour halt would be called if the sampp index future fell another 
20 points the same day 
if the sampp index fell a total of 50 points in one day that 
market could not reopen but the nyse would have the option of 
reopening after a twohour halt 
the experimental reforms are aimed at taming the wild price 
swings in both markets that some crash studies have attributed to a 
trading method called index arbitrage in which brokerages use 
large computers to sell stocks and buy stockindex futures or vice 
versa to profit from momentary price discrepancies 
the nyse implemented a temporary measure called the collar 
in february aimed at quelling the effect of index arbitrage 
the collar banned use of the nyses computer system for that 
method on days when the dow average rose or fell 50 points from the 
previous close but its effect was controversial some critics said 
that it worsened volatility by severing an important link between 
the cash and futures markets 
phelan said the new measures would supercede the collar limit 
which is scheduled to expire in august but he said the nyse 
reserved the right to impose additional restrictions if volatility 
returned 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880707-0161 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
police said thursday they had few clues to 
who punctured orange juice cartons with hypodermic needles at three 
suburban markets this week and left notes warning of poison 
a national expert on product tampering warned that widespread 
news coverage of the cases could prompt copycat crimes and 
noted there were more than 700 reports of product tampering across 
the country last year 
no one drank from any of the juice cartons discovered monday 
tuesday and wednesday at three supermarkets within a few miles in 
the san fernando valley suburbs police tests were incomplete but 
one grocery store test cleared the first carton of cyanide 
contamination 
investigators have yet to find anyone who saw any of the 
tampering and are hampered in fingerprint checks because of the 
number of people who handle cartons in stores said police lt fred 
nixon 
were treating it as very high priority despite the fact that 
we dont know for certain that there is contamination present in 
either case its still a crime nixon said 
police advised consumers particularly near the affected stores 
25 miles northwest of downtown to check cartons before buying 
the three supermarket chains involved vons hughes and alpha 
beta all stepped up security in stores in the area company 
spokesmen said involved were two national orange juice brands 
coca cola cos minute maid and procter amp gambles citrus hill 
in each case a twoquart carton of orange juice was removed 
from the refrigerator case and punctured with the needle from a 
hypodermic syringe the cartons with the needles still attached 
were found by customers or employees on shelves elsewhere in the 
markets each with a note attached suggesting poison had been 
injected 
california law makes threats of tampering with food or drugs a 
misdemeanor and actually contaminating a product a felony the fbi 
is evaluating the case to see if federal felony tampering statutes 
apply said spokesman fred reagan 
investigators withheld some details of the tampering to make it 
easier to identify possible imitators 
research suggests that one nationally publicized case of product 
tampering leads to 30 copycat crimes across the country said 
park elliott dietz a psychiatrist at the university of virginia in 
charlottesville who studies such cases and has consulted for the 
fbi 
the major determinant of how many cases there will be in the 
next three months is how widely this is publicized dietz said in 
a telephone interview the consensus of how to handle this is to 
make sure the public is informed about potential risk in that 
geographic area 
according to statistics from the food and drug administration 
threatened and actual product tampering increased ninefold in 1986 
to 1698 reported cases after the death of a new york woman who 
took a poisoned tylenol pain capsule 
in 1987 the fda received 774 consumer complaints of tampering 
with food drugs and other regulated products and confirmed 84 
cases of tampering with packages or their contents 
cases of threats combined with some form of tampering as in the 
california incidents are much more rare said richard swanson 
director of emergency operations for the fda he wasnt able to 
provide statistics on such cases 
</TEXT>
