<TEXT>
jesse jackson and his days in the 1960s civil 
rights movement are not topics of easy conversation on the home 
ground of the late rev martin luther king jr 
few among the civil rights old guard want to talk about 
jacksons time with kings southern christian leadership 
conference and those willing to discuss the subject sometimes 
paint a less than flattering picture of the man who went on to run 
for president 
kings widow coretta scott king declined to reminisce publicly 
about jackson except to say he was the one who told her king had 
been shot and instructed her to take the next thing smoking to 
memphis tenn 
ralph abernathy and andrew young kings top aides did not 
return repeated telephone calls seeking comment on jackson 
the rev joseph lowery the current sclc president and a jackson 
supporter paused for several minutes when asked for movement 
memories of the democratic presidential candidate 
i dont remember nothin he said 
atlanta city councilman hosea williams who worked in field 
operations for the sclc said jacksons desire to work with king 
led to a meteoric rise in the organization and a post running its 
chicago departments 
jesse was smart energetic charismatic he really impressed 
dr king williams said 
but jackson also had an obvious disdain for following rules 
williams said and would use the funds he raised for his chicago 
operations without prior approval of sclc officials 
king and the rest of the sclc executive council grew tired of 
jacksons rulebending williams said and emotions came to a head 
in late march 1968 during an atlanta meeting five days before his 
death king had a heated exchange with jackson and stormed out of 
the room in uncharacteristic anger 
he turned around and looked at jesse and said jesse if you 
want to start your own national organization i understand its ok 
with me but dont try to destroy me in the interim williams 
said 
after kings death jackson had other rifts with sclc officials 
into the early 1970s leading him to walk away from the 
organization and never return williams said 
one major source of friction with civil rights leaders was the 
bloody shirt incident 
jackson created an uproar when hours after kings 
assassination he appeared in chicago and on national television 
wearing a bloodstained turtleneck sweater and saying he had cradled 
king as he died civil rights leaders were outraged 
when i got up there abernathy was cradling docs head and 
andy had gone into the room to get a towel williams said we 
got doc in the car and they headed to the hospital abernathy went 
with him 
all at once i heard someone say i was the last man in the 
world king talked to i looked around and it was jesse with all 
the press around he said all this blood on my shirt i got it 
when i cradled his head 
williams said jackson was not on the memphis motel balcony when 
the shots were fired jackson had been standing in the parking lot 
with the chauffeur and the rev james bevel the sclc field 
strategist who brought jackson into the organization in 1965 
jackson generally declines to talk about the incident but the 
washington post quoted him in april as saying it happened the 
way i said it did 
later williams said kings aides gathered and pledged their 
support to abernathy kings best friend as the new president of 
sclc 
i remember jesse saying he was sick he said im going to my 
room what jesse did is jesse went to chicago williams said 
describing how kings horrified aides watched as jackson wore the 
bloodsmeared sweater on the today show and during hearings 
before the chicago city council 
some of those like andy and coretta and others have never been 
able to forgive jesse for that he said 
rep john lewis dga who worked with the student nonviolent 
coordinating committee during the 1960s is less accusatory than 
williams in his comments on jackson he said in an interview that 
criticism of jacksons movement activities stem from the fact that 
jackson didnt play the politics of the movement 
i think a great many older people and some not so old that 
were part of the movement felt threatened by jesse jackson by his 
leadership by his ability lewis said he had some idea about 
what direction he wanted to move and set about doing just that 
he made a very signtion in chicago to give the 
movement a solid presence in a large urban area outside the 
south lewis added i dont think jesse deliberately went out 
on a course to usurp power in the sclc 
bevel a staunch republican who currently works withificant contribu 
a chicago 
youth organization he formed said i brought jesse jackson into 
sclc i recommended jesse he said there was a struggle within 
the organization against the recommendation but he was set up in 
chicago to set that operation into motion 
we were in memphis together when king was shot bevel said 
king got shot about 6 oclock and ralph abernathy told me to 
go up to the temple to tell the people because him and andy and 
bernard lee were gnature 
lincoln was nominated on the third ballot won the election over 
the divided democrats and reluctantly appointed cameron to the 
treasury 
the last convention year in which both major parties opened 
their conventions with the outcome uncertain was in 1952 
gen dwight d eisenhower beat out ohio sen robert taft the 
choice of conservatives for the gop nomination on the first ballot 
the uncertainty was greater on the democratic side eleven 
candidates were nominated the frontrunner sen estes kefauver of 
tennessee could muster only 28 percent on the first ballot 
democratic kingmakers began to look elsewhere 
their eyes fell on illinois democratic governor adlai e 
stevenson who had delivered a stirring keynote address 
stevenson refused to run 
a draft movement was formed and on the third ballot it succeeded 
the longest convention in the history of either party was the 
democratic conclave of 1924 in new york 
there were 103 roll calls over 17 days 
new york gov al smith passed william gibbs mcadoo secretary of 
the treasury in the woodrow wilson administration on the 86th 
ballot of the political marathon in a convention divided between 
rural and big city elements 
humorist will rogers complained that new york city had invited 
delegates to visit the place not live there permanently 
mcadoo recaptured the lead on the 94th but released his 
delegates on the 99th 
wall street lawyer john w davis who had received just 31 votes 
on the first ballot finally prevailed on the 103rd and marched off 
to defeat by calvin coolidge in november 
it was the republican convention of 1920 that produced that 
classic symbol of a brokered convention the smokefilled room 
there is disagreement on whether there was actually a 
smokefilled room in chicago where party bosses turned to sen 
warren harding of ohio 
but there is no disagreement that the term has entered american 
political history as a powerful symbol of a manipulated convention 
according to the boller account harry m daughtery hardings 
campaign manager had predicted four months before the convention 
that delegates would deadlock and weary party bosses would select 
harding in a hotel room meeting in the early morning hours 
actually harding was called before republican leaders at 200 
am told he might win the nomination the next day and asked 
whether there was anything in his background that might prove 
embarrassing or harm his effectiveness as candidate or president 
harding was left alone to think about it then declared there 
was nothing no obstacle to his candidacy a declaration that 
might have been less than candid considering hardings affair at 
the time with a married woman 
after it was all over according to boller someone called 
pennsylvania sen boies penrose who had helped orchestrate 
hardings selection and said he hoped hardings weakness for women 
wouldnt be brought up in the campaign 
no worries about that said penrose 
well just throw a halo around his handsome head and 
everything will be all right 
