<TEXT>
irving bank corp has vowed to appeal a state 
court ruling striking down a provision of its poison pill 
defense aimed at thwarting bank of new yorks hostile merger 
efforts 
supreme court justice herman cahn on wednesday granted a 
preliminary injunction against the provision ruling it unfairly 
discriminated against bank of new york and the company would suffer 
irreparable harm from irvings takeover defense 
the defense would allow all of irving shareholders except a 
hostile suitor to buy 400 worth of irving shares for 200 if any 
suitor bought more than 20 percent of irving stock without the 
support of irvings management such provisions are intended to 
make unsolicited takeover bids prohibitively expensive 
irving attorney robert a falise said the bank planned to appeal 
cahns ruling which he called erroneous 
but falise said he was pleased the judge did not reject irvings 
entire poison pill which adheres to a new york state antitakeover 
law that prevents an unfriendly merger for at least five years 
bank of new york reaffirmed its outstanding buyout offer and 
said it would seek a 60day extension from the federal reserve 
board for conditional approval of its proposed merger with irving 
the feds approval was due to run out saturday 
rodgin cohen an attorney for bank of new york said cahns 
ruling should remove the single biggest question they the fed 
had and that was the ability to complete the merger 
mark alpert a banking analyst with bear stearns amp co 
predicted the fed would grant an extension if the fed had wanted 
to stop this the takeover battle they would have spoken up now 
alpert said it was unlikely bank of new york would attempt to 
amass a larger stake in irving for fear that irving would win an 
appeal that would trigger the poison pill 
he also noted that even if an appeals court ruled in favor of 
bank of new york the state antitakeover law would force bank of 
new york to operate irving as a separate subsidiary 
cahns decision came a day after irvings board of directors 
accepted an improved merger offer from a friendly suitor staterun 
banca commerciale italiana spa italys second largest bank 
the milanbased bank offered tuesday to sweeten its bid for a 51 
percent stake of irving with warrants entitling shareholders to buy 
newly issued irving stock at 65 a share over the next seven years 
stockholders would receive one warrant for every four shares they 
currently owned 
the offer was contingent upon irving keeping its poison pill 
intact 
banca commerciale previously had offered 80 a share for 51 
percent of irvings 185 million common shares outstanding or 
about 760 million the blended value was as much as 7650 per 
share 
the merger proposal is part of a complex defensive restructuring 
plan that includes among other things sale of irving assets 
costcutting measures and a special cash dividend 
irving said the latest offer made the overall transaction worth 
at least 7950 per share which the banks board deemed superior 
to bank of new yorks best and final bid 
however estimates of the value of the offer have differed 
widely 
bank of new york which owns a 49 percent stake in irving is 
offering 15 in cash and 1575 shares of its own stock for each of 
irvings common shares outstanding the offer is valued at around 
68 a share or 12 billion 
the bank had offered to sweeten the rare hostile bid by slightly 
raising the stock portion of the bid and adding other shareholder 
incentives including a special cash dividend if irving agreed to 
abandon its poison pill 
