<TEXT>
a study of the fees paid to investment bankers in 
friendly business mergers concludes that such payments which may 
total millions of dollars are no more excessive than the 
transaction fees paid to real estate agents 
researchers william curt hunter and mary beth walker of the 
federal reserve bank of atlanta stated their review of 125 friendly 
mergers between 1979 and 1985 indicated the bankers fees though 
large in absolute terms are only a small percentage of the 
economic value created by the mergers 
on average when measured against the gain that the merger 
creates for the new entity the fee approximates that of a 
typical real estate transaction said the researchers who 
figured the average fee equalled about 66 percent of the economic 
gain created by the mergers 
furthermore the investment bankers fees averaged a very 
reasonable less than 1 percent of the total transaction price 
with the highest being 34 percent of the price hunter said 
the study was published in the atlanta feds economic review 
publication 
the researchers limited their survey to friendly mergers of 
public companies and did not look at those where investment banks 
provided only fairness or underwriting services walker said it was 
the first survey to compare fees with services rendered 
the mergers ranged in value from 34 million to 6 billion with 
fees ranging from 100000 to 20 million 
the two largest fees came from the 28 billion deal in 1984 
that joined beatrice foods co and esmark inc and the 5 billion 
merger in 1985 of allied corp with the signal cos inc 
hunter said each deal paid 20 million to the investment banks 
involved first boston corp and lazard freres and co in 
beatriceesmark lazard salomon brothers and oppenheimer and co 
in the alliedsignal merger 
the wave of mergers and acquisitions in recent years has brought 
more attention to the fees paid investment bankers with some 
critics claiming the fees are excessive 
trade publications have discussed the fees in articles with 
titles like merger fees that bend the mind and wall streets 
overpaid young stars the merger departments of three separate 
wall street firms each earned 200 million in 1985 
hunter said the attention and worry have caused some 
mergerminded companies to consider a doityourself approach 
but hunter and ms walker argued against bypassing the 
investment bankers 
bringing together of buyer and seller and advising on what 
price to pay from that point of view investment bankers seem 
to be well worth their fee hunter said in an interview 
firms contemplating a doityourself approach simply because 
fees charged by professional merger intermediaries appear excessive 
would do well to scrutinize the costs and benefits of 
selfsearch hunter and ms walker wrote 
the researchers note that investment banks traditionally have 
provided a range of services including underwriting marketmaking 
and advice on capital structure dividend policy mergers 
acquisitions and divestitures 
while other financial institutions provide many of these same 
services the investment banks specialization and expertise in 
corporate financial matters along with their position overlooking 
capital markets as a whole give them a comparative advantage that 
permits them to command handsome fees they wrote 
hunter also said investment bankers are constantly gathering and 
assessing information on corporate assets research that would have 
to be done otherwise by individual suitors 
</TEXT>
