<TEXT>
the big us airlines that fly overseas say they 
are taking no chances with retaliation from terrorists and have 
stepped up their defenses in response to the us navys downing of 
an iran air jetliner 
we take the threat seriously said stephen heckscher a 
spokesman in london for trans world airlines international 
division 
the incident in the persian gulf last weekend which killed 
nearly 300 civilians has raised fears of a retaliatory attack by 
iran 
political experts have suggested that revenge could take the 
form of a terrorist assault against us military bases or 
personnel overseas or against other american targets including 
commercial airline flights 
bob kierce twas director of international security said the 
airline has taken steps to ensure that its already tight security 
precautions are being exercised to the fullest 
kierce said the airline also has added some new measures at 
several airports which he declined to name those measures include 
having a senior member of management on duty whenever a twa plane 
is on the ground at those locations 
twa the nations seventhlargest airline has been the target 
of some of the most notorious terrorist attacks against jetliners 
in recent years in june 1985 lebanese shiite moslems hijacked a 
twa flight over the mediterranean and diverted it to beirut where 
they killed a passenger the hostages werent freed until 17 days 
later 
terrorists set off a bomb in the passenger cabin of a twa 
jetliner over greece in april 1986 killing four americans 
other us airlines that carry passengers abroad also have been 
on alert following the iran air disaster beefing up security in 
the midst of the peak summer travel season experts say 
like twa most big carriers have their own security divisions 
but also contract with outside security companies for passenger 
screening in airports and other protective services 
many of the airlines are touchy about security and refuse to 
discuss what theyre doing but they emphasize that antiterrorist 
defenses are always intensified after such an incident 
the airlines dont need a crystal ball its so obvious 
said dick lally assistant vice president for security at the air 
transport association a washingtonbased trade group that 
represents the nations major carriers 
the airlines have most likely tightened their security in 
consultation with the federal aviation administration lally 
suggested 
