<TEXT>
a massive oil rig fire off the coast of scotland 
will worsen a shortage of north sea oil but the disaster is not 
likely to have a big impact on the industry experts say 
the fatal accident which caused a jump in world oil prices 
thursday prompted the governments department of energy to 
postpone the process for granting new offshore licenses which 
would open up more areas for exploration the department had been 
scheduled to announce on thursday the blocks for which it was 
inviting bids for the licenses 
because of what happened weve decided to postpone that at 
the moment said a department spokesman who spoke anonymously in 
keeping with british practice 
the price of brent blend the most widely traded international 
crude oil jumped on thursday to 1505 a barrel for september 
delivery up 32 cents from late wednesday 
occidental petroleum co owner of the piper alpha rig said a 
gas leak apparently was to blame for the disaster 
the rig produced 167200 barrels a day the company said a 
barrel contains 42 gallons 
in addition to the piper oil field five other fields were shut 
down the department said they were the claymore tartan 
highland scapa and petronella fields it said 
that meant production was cut by a total of about 220000 
barrels a day to 250000 barrels a day or about onetenth of the 
british sectors production the department and analysts said 
theres pressure on the immediate availability for north sea 
crude said philip morgan an oil analyst with the london 
investment firm warburg securities 
lucy mullins an oil analyst with the london investment firm 
barclays de zoete wedd ltd added however thats going to be 
fairly shortterm 
the related fields should be back in production in a week and 
piper alpha probably will be out of production for up to a year 
ms mullins said 
morgan said the industry already was experiencing a shortage 
because of regular maintenance which oil companies generally do in 
the summmer when the weather is milder 
north sea oil production in the british sector averages 2 
million barrels a day the department of energy says production is 
down 400000 barrels a day from that level because of the 
maintenance morgan said 
producers of the organization of petroleum exporting countries 
of which britain is not a member will step in to meet demand ms 
mullins said 
the oil price also has been boosted by favorable statistics 
released this week morgan said 
there is starting to be a perception that the glut in world 
supplies in general is not as bad as people thought morgan said 
occidental petroleums production wont be severely affected by 
the fire because it has other outlets ms mullins said 
there were concerns about claims against the company however 
and occidental petroleums stock fell 50 cents to 2625 in early 
trading on the new york stock exchange the stock price of british 
petroleum co plc the biggest producer in the british sector fell 
3 cents to 449 in afternoon trading on londons stock exchange 
the disaster could prove expensive for the north sea oil 
producers in general morgan said 
obviously questions are going to be raised about safety which 
might involve companies in a lot more expenditure morgan said 
the british sector of the north sea oil fields runs from the 
shetland islands north of scotland down to east anglia on englands 
southeast coast covering hundreds of thousands of square miles 
the first british sector gas fields were discovered in 1964 and oil 
production began in 1975 the department of energy said 
the sector employed 28000 people in offshore facilities at the 
end of last year it said 
there are 123 fixed installations including the piper alpha 
platform in the british sector with 40 mobile rigs the 
department said 
