<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880707-0207 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the securities and exchange commission voted 
thursday to limit the ability of american companies to weaken the 
voting power of their stockholders as way of fighting hostile 
corporate raids 
the new oneshare onevote rule approved 41 does not 
altogether ban dual classes of common stock but rather spells out 
how shares with reduced voting power can be issued 
one popular takeover defense in which companies entice 
stockholders into giving up their voting rights by offering a 
special onetime dividend would be prohibited 
also barred would be rules that require a stock purchaser to 
wait sometimes for several years before newly acquired shares 
accrue full voting rights 
companies will have to comply with the new sec rule if they want 
their stock traded on an exchange or through the national 
association of securities dealers automated quotation system 
however in another voting rights area the sec decided to defer 
to the states in states that allow it companies will be permitted 
to deny voting power to takeover raiders unless the other 
shareholders approve 
about a dozen states have adopted such laws and the sec in 
friendofthecourt briefs has argued that they improperly 
interfere with national securities markets 
in unrelated action the commission voted unanimously to back 
off from recommending congressional legislation barring brokerage 
firms from requiring customers to agree in advance to settle 
disputes before an arbitration panel 
state securities regulators and others have been arguing that 
socalled predispute arbitration clauses in the fine print of 
account agreements are unfair because they require customers in 
some cases unwittingly to sign away their right to sue in court 
before they know the nature of any disagreement that may arise 
richard g ketchum director of the secs division of market 
regulation said he doubted the new oneshare onevote rule would 
have a dramatic effect on takeovers but he conceded that in a few 
cases takeovers would be easier because the rule eliminates some 
extremely effective defenses 
commissioner charles c cox the only member to vote against the 
rule said he believed the sec was intruding into an area that has 
traditionally been left to states the chartering and governance of 
corporations 
i believe this is an improper use of the listing standards to 
tamper with corporate governance he said 
however sec chairman david s ruder said the rule is structured 
to be as least intrusive as possible 
companies will still be permitted to issue new shares with 
diluted voting power dilutedpower shares can also be issued to 
accomplish a merger and private companies going public will be 
able to issue both strongvoting and weakvoting shares 
however corporations will not be able to issue supershares 
that have more voting power than common stock already issued that 
would have allowed company insiders such as managers to buy up 
the strong shares to acquire control over the company 
stocks of foreign companies traded in the united states will be 
exempted from the regulations the 359 us companies that had 
disparate voting rights before thursday will also be exempted as 
will the stocks of small companies listed in the nasds socalled 
pink sheets and traded by brokers over the telephone 
despite the exceptions the rule drew praise from the united 
shareholders association which is headed by texas oilman and 
takeover specialist t boone pickens jr 
the secs action helps to restore democracy to corporate 
america pickens said in a statement 
commission debate over the rule approved thursday began nearly 
two years ago when the new york stock exchange in september 1986 
asked for sec permission to drop its 60yearold oneshare 
onevote standard 
exchange officials said they were dropping the standard 
reluctantly out of fear of losing business to the american stock 
exchange which had more liberal rules and the nasd which had no 
such standard 
sen william proxmire dwis chairman of the senate banking 
committee and others have argued that the sec does not have 
jurisdiction over the matter and should defer to congress 
however commissioner edward h fleischman said congress has not 
acted in two years and that the law requires the sec to approve or 
disapprove changes in exchange rules 
on the arbitration issue the sec voted to ask the stock 
exchanges and the nasd to study predispute clauses and to report 
back to the commission by oct 15 
nevertheless reps rick boucher dva john d dingell 
dmich and edward j markey dmass have gone ahead and 
introduced a bill anyway 
the head of the north american securities administrators 
association which represents state regulators called the sec 
decision disappointing 
small investors will see the commission failure to act as 
another sign that the deck is stacked against them said james c 
meyer president of the association and tennessees top securities 
regulator 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

