<TEXT>
three measures of the nations money supply rose 
in the week ended june 27 the federal reserve board reported 
thursday 
the fed said the narrowest measure known as m1 rose 400 million 
to a seasonally adjusted 7788 billion from a revised 7784 
billion the previous week 
a broader measure m2 rose to a seasonally adjusted 3020 
trillion from 3018 trillion the previous week 
an even broader measure m3 increased to a seasonally adjusted 
3809 trillion from 3804 trillion 
m1 includes cash in circulation deposits in checking accounts 
and nonbank travelers checks m2 is m1 plus accounts like savings 
deposits and moneymarket mutual funds m3 is m2 plus lessliquid 
accounts such as certificates of deposit in minimum denominations 
of 100000 
in judging its monetary policy the fed has indicated it is 
monitoring the value of the dollar commodity prices and the 
difference between short and longterm interest rates as well as 
money supply trends 
in other reports 
the federal reserve bank of new york reported commercial and 
industrial loans at major new york city banks fell 857 million 
compared with a decline of 561 million a week earlier 
the federal reserve said bank borrowings from the federal 
reserve system averaged 1301 billion up from 541 million 
the federal reserve bank of st louis reprted that the monetary 
base the seasonally adjusted total of member bank reserves held at 
federal reserve banks and cash in bank vaults and in circulation 
was 2789 billion in the twoweek period ended wednesday up from 
2782 billion two weeks earlier 
