<TEXT>
the securities and exchange commission on 
thursday backed off from recommending legislation that would 
guarantee investors the right to sue their stock broker in court 
the commission had been considering asking congress to outlaw 
clauses in brokerage account agreements requiring customers to 
settle disputes through industrysponsored arbitration panels 
rather than through the courts 
but by a 50 vote the commission decided instead to ask stock 
exchanges and other organizations that run arbitration systems to 
study the matter and report back by oct 15 
rep edward j markey dmass chairman of the house 
subcommittee with jurisdiction over the securities markets said 
the sec had caved in to industry lobbying with its decision 
apparently there was a fullcourt press by the industry that 
was successful markey said i think the industry stared 
into the secs eyes on this issue and the sec blinked 
when the commission discussed the arbitration clauses last 
month the legislative recommendation looked headed for approval 
it was supported by sec chairman david s ruder and member aulana 
l peters commissioner charles c cox said he was inclined to 
favor it but wanted to hear from securities firms which strongly 
opposed banning the clauses 
but on thursday ruder retreated from his earlier support he 
said he was persuaded to defer action after learning the industry 
would at least favor disclosure notices to customers explaining the 
meaning of the clauses 
an sec survey found that 39 percent of cash accounts carry 
arbitration agreements and that firms holding another 40 percent 
were considering using such clauses 
but ruder said many firms that were once looking into using the 
clauses for cash accounts appear to be holding off at least for 
now he also said some regional firms have recently made a point of 
advertising that they will open cash accounts without arbitration 
clauses 
however nearly all firms surveyed 95 percent require 
arbitration agreements for option and margin accounts where the 
risk of loss is greater 
proponents of the clauses argue that customers are free to 
negotiate the clauses out of the contract and that firms have a 
right to set the conditions under which theyre willing to do 
business 
administration officials including beryl sprinkel chairman of 
the council of economic advisers had sent letters to the sec 
criticizing staff proposals on arbitration clauses 
despite the lack of sec support reps rick boucher dva john 
d dingell dmich and edward j markey dmass have introduced 
legislation anyway 
the bill is backed by state securities regulators and others who 
say arbitration clauses are unfair because they require customers 
to sign away their right to sue before they know the nature of any 
disagreement that may arise 
the head of the north american securities administrators 
association which represents state regulators called the sec 
decision disappointing 
if the commissions mistake goes uncorrected investors will 
end up having only those rights which the securities industry 
chooses to give them small investors will see the commission 
failure to act as another sign that the deck is stacked against 
them said james c meyer president of the association and 
tennessees top securities regulator 
ruder however said i want to make it clear that this 
is not a decision to deemphasize consumer interest in the 
securities industry 
</TEXT>
