<DOCNO> AP880707-0220 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
sun co incs board of directors on 
thursday approved a major restructuring plan that will spin off the 
companys 48 billion domestic oil and gas exploration and 
production business into an independent company and trim its work 
force by more than 1000 
the plan also calls for the nations 10th largest oil company to 
expand its international exploration and production operations as 
well as its refining and marketing business which will be retained 
by the restructured sun company officials said 
it comes two days after sun announced it had agreed to buy 
atlantic petroleum corp a northeast refiner and retailer for 
513 million from oil trader john duess 
the reorganization is projected as a majorcost savings move for 
the radnorbased company said peter waitneight vice president of 
corporate financing 
the earnings have not been growing in the rather weak market 
for crude oil and natural gas waitneight said in a telephone 
interview 
he said company officials believe that payroll reductions and 
independent management structures for the separate companies would 
result in higher earnings that would boost profits 
under the plan current sun shareholders would receive a 
oneforone taxfree distribution of stock in the newly created sun 
exploration and production co which will handle domestic oil and 
gas exploration and production 
the redistribution is subject to approval by shareholders and 
dependent on the internal revenue service granting it taxfree 
status 
the new company to be headquartered in dallas would become the 
largest independent oil and gas producer in north america with 
approximately 48 billion in assets and 16 billion in revenue in 
1987 sun officials said 
the original sun would restructure with more than 9 billion in 
assets excluding the domestic oil and gas exploration and 
production business sun totaled 91 billion in revenue last year 
waitneight said the distribution would be presented for 
shareholders consideration during a special meeting in early 
october with distribution of shares if approved planned for the 
end of october 
reduction of the work force will begin immediately waitneight 
said 
about 800 sun workers employed in the new companys operations 
most of them in the western united states will lose their jobs 
waitneight said 
another 250 workers at the restructured sun most of them in the 
east and many in the philadelphia area also will lose their jobs 
he said 
company officials said some employees would be offered early 
retirment incentives but waitneight would not specify how many 
sun officials expect the restructuring to produce 65 million in 
aftertax savings for sun eampp each year and 15 million for the 
restructured sun each year most of that through payroll reductions 
the driving force behind this decision is to enhance value for 
holders of sun stock said robert mcclements jr chairman and 
chief executive officer of sun 
robert p hauptfuhrer suns president and chief operating 
officer was named by the sun board as the chairman and chief 
executive officer of the newly created sun eampp james mccormick 
who heads the companys exploration and production operations will 
become the president and chief operating officer of sun eampp 
sun company has more than 20000 employees in the united states 
and eight other countries it has refineries in pennsylvania ohio 
oklahoma puerto rico and canada and mines coal in five states sun 
sells gasoline under the sunoco brand 
atlantic has one refinery with 440 employees in philadelphia 
owns 571 gas stations and supplies another 400 independent 
stations primarily in pennsylvania new york and new jersey 
the atlantic purchase also includes 30 oil terminals owned by 
atlantic plus its 986mile products pipeline system from its 
refinery to pittsburgh pa and rochester and tonawanda ny 
sun reported revenue of 239 billion in the first quarter of 
1988 compared to 226 billion in the first quarter of 1987 net 
income for the first quarter of 1988 was 60 million or 57 per 
share of common stock a 58 percent increase from the 38 million 
or 35 per share of common stock in the first quarter of 1987 
 
</TEXT>
